
[1]spurn

   SPURN, v.t. [L., spur, kicking.]

   1. To kick; to drive back or away, as with the foot.

   2. To reject with disdain; to scorn to receive or accept. What
   multitudes of rational beings spurn the offers of eternal happiness!

   3. To treat with contempt.

                                 SPURN, v.i.

   1. To manifest disdain in rejecting any thing; as, to spurn at the
   gracious offers of pardon.

   2. To make contemptuous opposition; to manifest disdain in resistance.

   Nay more, to spurn at your most royal image.

   3. To kick or toss up the heels.

   The drunken chairman in the kennel spurns.

           SPURN, n. Disdainful rejection; contemptuous treatment.

   The insolence of office, and the spurns that patient merit of the
   unworthy takes.
